# Neural Reversi — GGS init script (example).
#
# Usage:
#
#   cli ggs --user MYLOGIN --script init.ggs
#
# Each line is sent verbatim to GGS right after the TCP handshake. GGS is
# prompt-driven: the FIRST line is consumed by the `Enter login` prompt,
# the SECOND line by the `Enter your password` prompt. There is no
# `login` keyword — do not write `login MYLOGIN MYPASS` on one line, or
# GGS will reject the whole line as a login name and every subsequent
# script line will be consumed as the next prompt in sequence, usually
# logging you in under the wrong account.
#
# The --user flag you pass on the command line MUST match the login name
# used on the first script line, otherwise the engine cannot recognise
# which side in a match is ours and will decline to play.
#
# GGS login constraints (from the live server):
#   - 2–8 characters
#   - cannot start with `.` or `_`
#   - cannot contain `,` or `\`
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------

# 1. Login name (answers the `Enter login` prompt).
MYLOGIN

# 2. Password (answers the `Enter your password` prompt).
MYPASS

# 3. Select the Othello service so the `ts`, `tp`, `ta`, `tw`, ...
#    shorthand aliases resolve to `/os`. Equivalent to `var _service /os`.
mso

# 4. Default to unrated. Flip to `ts rated +` once you're ready.
ts rated -

# 5. Accept up to 3 pending ask offers at a time (pending, not concurrent —
#    this engine only auto-plays one match at a time).
ts open 3

# 6. Dump the list of currently-online /os players so you can see who's
#    around as soon as the session starts.
ts who 8

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------
# From here on, drive the session by typing into stdin, e.g.:
#
#   ta ant                   # challenge the built-in `ant` bot
#   ts ask 8 2:00 ant        # explicit 8x8, 2-minute match vs ant
#   ts accept .5             # accept incoming ask .5
#   ts decline .5            # decline incoming ask .5
#   ts resign                # resign the current match
#   t someone hello          # private tell
#
# The engine auto-plays moves once a match starts, derives its own
# thinking time from the server clock, and sends PASS automatically
# when it has no legal moves.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------
